validators), and runs inside a VM isolation environment (or directly on a host). All logs are stored locally.\n10: \n11: **Core features**:\n12: \n13: - Tools and skills share JSON Schema I/O (strings, arrays, objects).\n14: - Skills support **eager tool calls** (`{{tool:name ...}}`) that execute before the LLM request.\n15: - Skills support **parameter substitution** (`{{key}}`) where `key` is a field from the invocation parameters (e.g., `{{goal}}`).\n16: - **Validators** (optional chain of tools) process the LLM response; validators are simple tool names (future extension for transformation bindings).\n17: - **Dependencies** declared per skill (tools and other skills required) – **must be checked before execution**.\n18: - **Timeout enforcement** for all tool executions (30 seconds default).\n19: - **Docker execution mode**: Tools can run inside isolated containers (default Ubuntu 22.04) with configurable trust levels (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW), shared container pools, custom images, and `apt` dependencies. Skills can bring up multi‑service environments using `docker-compose.yml`.\n20: - Performance monitoring (optional, for future C++ optimization).\n21: - Session replay via local JSON Lines logs.\n22: \n23: This specification includes **architectural and procedural guardrails** that would have prevented common implementation omissions, such as missing dependency checks, ignored parameter substitution, absent subprocess timeouts, and incomplete `args` mode handling. The Docker sub‑module is a **required** extension for containerized execution.\n24: \n25: ---\n26: \n27: ## 2. Component Specifications (C++ Interfaces)\n28: \n29: The following interfaces are defined in `agent_interfaces.h`. They use modern C++17/20 features (`std::variant`, `std::optional`, smart pointers). No inheritance except abstract base classes.\n30: \n31: **Key types**:\n32: \n33: ```cpp\n34: using StructuredValue = std::variant<nullptr_t, bool, double, std::string,\n35:                                      std::vector<StructuredValue>,\n36:                                      std::unordered_map<std::string, StructuredValue>>;\n37: using JSONSchema = std::unordered_map<std::string, StructuredValue>;\n38: ```\n39: \n40: ### 2.1 Core Data Structures\n41: \n42: ```cpp\n43: enum class TrustLevel {\n44:     HIGH,      // shared container across all high-trust tools\n45:     MEDIUM,    // shared container across all medium-trust tools\n46:     LOW        // one container per (image, tool name) combination\n47: };\n48: \n49: struct Tool {\n50:     std::string name;\n51:     std::string description;\n52:     std::string command;\n53:     // \"stdin\": params JSON is serialized and piped to the command's stdin.\n54:     // \"args\":  params is a JSON object; each top-level key-value pair is passed as a command-line argument\n55:     //          in the form --key=value (if value is string/number) or just value (if key is \"_\").\n56:     //          For a non-object params, the whole value is passed as a single argument.\n57:     //          Arguments are shell-escaped.\n58:     std::string inputMode = \"stdin\";\n59: \n60:     // Docker execution (optional – if dockerImage empty, run on host)\n61:     std::string dockerImage;                     // e.g., \"ubuntu:22.04\"\n62:     TrustLevel trustLevel = TrustLevel::MEDIUM;\n63:     bool useContainerPool = true;                // false = ephemeral docker run --rm\n64:     std::vector<std::string> aptDependencies;    // packages to install via apt\n65:     int timeoutSecs = 30;                        // per-tool timeout override\n66: };\n67: \n68: struct ToolCall {\n69:     std::string id;\n70:     std::string name;\n71:     json arguments;\n72: };\n73: \n74: struct ToolSchema {\n75:     std::string name;\n76:     std::string description;\n77:     json inputSchema;\n78: };\n79: \n80: struct ValidatorBinding {\n81:     std::string toolName;\n82:     std::optional<std::string> transform; // future: JSONPath binding\n83: };\n84: \n85: struct Prompt {\n86:     std::string name;\n87:     std::string description;\n88:     std::string prompt;                   // may contain {{tool:...}} and {{key}} placeholders\n89:     std::vector<std::string> dependencies;    // tool and prompt names required\n90:     std::vector<ValidatorBinding> validators; // post-LLM processing chain\n91:     std::string ns;                            // namespace context for qualified-name resolution\n92:     std::string component;                     // component context for qualified-name resolution\n93: \n94:     // Docker compose support\n95:     std::string composeFile;                     // path to docker-compose.yml (relative to skill dir)\n96:     std::vector<std::string> aptDependencies;    // rolled up into container(s) used by prompt's tools\n97: };\n98: ```\n99: \n100: ### 2.2 Abstract Interfaces\n101: \n102: ```cpp\n103: class SkillRegistry {\n104: public:\n105:     virtual ~SkillRegistry() = default;\n106:     virtual bool loadFromDirectory(const std::string& path) = 0;\n107:     virtual std::optional<Tool> getTool(const std::string& name) const = 0;\n108:     virtual std::optional<Skill> getSkill(const std::string& name) const = 0;\n109:     virtual std::vector<std::string> listTools() const = 0;\n110:     virtual std::vector<std::string> listSkills() const = 0;\n111:     virtual bool addTool(const Tool& tool) = 0;\n112:     virtual bool addSkill(const Skill& skill) = 0;\n113: };\n114: \n115: class ToolRunner {\n116: public:\n117:     virtual ~ToolRunner() = default;\n118:     // Runs a tool with the given parameters. Must enforce timeout from tool.timeoutSecs.\n119:     // Returns the stdout output as a string (or JSON for structured outputs).\n120:     // On timeout, returns a string starting with \"ERROR: timeout\".\n121:     // On command failure, returns a string starting with \"ERROR:\".\n122:     virtual json run(const Tool& tool, const json& params) = 0;\n123: \n124:     // Streaming variant: returns immediately with a StreamHandle.\n125:     // onChunk is called from a background thread with (chunk, direction).\n126:     // Default implementation delegates to CommandRunner::runStreaming.\n127:     virtual a0::StreamHandle runStreaming(const Tool& tool,\n128:                                            const json& params,\n129:                                            a0::StreamCallback onChunk);\n130: };\n131: \n132: class InferenceProvider {\n133: public:\n134:     virtual ~InferenceProvider() = default;\n135:     virtual std::string complete(const std::string& systemPrompt,\n136:                                   const std::string& userPrompt) = 0;\n137:     virtual void setMockUrl(const std::string& url) = 0;\n138: };\n139: \n140: struct ContextFrame {\n141:     std::string role;\n142:     std::string content;\n143: };\n144: \n145: class ContextManager {\n146: public:\n147:     virtual ~ContextManager() = default;\n148:     virtual void push(const ContextFrame& frame) = 0;\n149:     virtual ContextFrame pop() = 0;\n150:     virtual ContextFrame peek() const = 0;\n151:     virtual size_t size() const = 0;\n152:     virtual void clear() = 0;\n153:     virtual std::vector<ContextFrame> snapshot() const = 0;\n154: };\n155: \n156: class DependencyResolver {\n157: public:\n158:     virtual ~DependencyResolver() = default;\n159:     virtual bool checkToolDependencies(const Tool& tool) const = 0;\n160:     virtual bool checkPromptDependencies(const Prompt& prompt) const = 0;\n161:     virtual std::vector<std::string> missingDependencies(const Prompt& prompt) const = 0;\n162: };\n163: \n164: class SkillRunner {\n165: public:\n166:     virtual ~SkillRunner() = default;\n167:     // Expands prompt.prompt by:\n168:     //   1. Replacing {{key}} placeholders with values from params (where key\n... (output truncated at 8192 bytes)","role":"tool","tool_call_id":"call_00_lcvzSoNMsbvQLMRp3W9e1366"},{"content":"","role":"assistant","tool_calls":[{"function":{"arguments":"{\"file_path\":\"/home/pc/projects/opensassi/a0/.a0/worktrees/a0-session-7aaf7148/technical-specification.md\",\"offset\":168}","name":"read"},"id":"call_00_tczmVLDMwyXUPPyHXArJ4550","type":"function"}]},{"content":"168:     //   1. Replacing {{key}} placeholders with values from params (where key matches a top-level field).\n169:     //   2. Replacing {{tool:name key=\"value\" ...}} placeholders with the result of executing the named tool.\n170:     //   3. Replacing {{tool_call:qualified_name}} placeholders with the short name.\n171:     virtual std::string expandPrompt(const Prompt& prompt, const json& params) = 0;\n172:     // Runs the validator chain. If any validator returns a string starting with \"ERROR:\",\n173:     // the final result is prefixed with \"VALIDATOR_ERROR:\".\n174:     virtual json runValidators(const Prompt& prompt, const json& input) = 0;\n175:     // Executes the prompt: expandPrompt -> InferenceProvider.complete() -> runValidators.\n176:     // Before calling complete, it must verify that all dependencies are present (using DependencyResolver).\n177:     virtual json execute(const Prompt& prompt, const json& params) = 0;\n178: \n179:     // Streaming variant: executes the prompt with streaming tool invocations.\n180:     virtual a0::StreamHandle executeStreaming(const Prompt& prompt,\n181:                                                const json& params,\n182:                                                a0::StreamCallback onChunk) = 0;\n183: \n184:     virtual void setGlobalVar(const std::string& key, const std::string& value) = 0;\n185:     virtual void setGlobalVars(const std::unordered_map<std::string, std::string>& vars) = 0;\n186: };\n187: \n188: class SchemaInferenceEngine {\n189: public:\n190:     virtual ~SchemaInferenceEngine() = default;\n191:     virtual Tool inferTool(const std::string& naturalLanguageDescription) = 0;\n192:     virtual Prompt inferPrompt(const std::string& naturalLanguageDescription) = 0;\n193: };\n194: \n195: class AgentCore {\n196: public:\n197:     virtual ~AgentCore() = default;\n198:     virtual bool init(const std::string& componentsDir) = 0;\n199:     // Processes a user goal. Matches prompts by exact name (case-sensitive) against the goal string.\n200:     // If no exact match, uses SchemaInferenceEngine to infer a new prompt.\n201:     // If inference also fails, enters the forked tool-calling loop (xRunForkedLoop).\n202:     virtual json processGoal(const std::string& goal) = 0;\n203:     // Streaming variant: processes a goal with streaming tool invocations.\n204:     virtual a0::StreamHandle processGoalStreaming(const std::string& goal,\n205:                                                    a0::StreamCallback onChunk) = 0;\n206:     virtual bool resumeSession(const std::string& sessionId) = 0;\n207:     virtual std::string currentSessionId() const = 0;\n208:     virtual void run() = 0;\n209: };\n210: \n211: // === Docker Integration Interfaces ===\n212: // Full implementations reside in ./src/docker/\n213: \n214: class ContainerManager {\n215: public:\n216:     virtual ~ContainerManager() = default;\n217:     virtual std::string acquireContainer(const Tool& tool) = 0;\n218:     virtual std::string execInContainer(const std::string& containerId,\n219:                                         const std::string& command,\n220:                                         const std::string& stdinData = \"\") = 0;\n221:     virtual void pruneIdleContainers() = 0;\n222: };\n223: \n224: class ComposeManager {\n225: public:\n226:     virtual ~ComposeManager() = default;\n227:     virtual std::string startEnvironment(const Prompt& prompt, const std::string& skillDirectory) = 0;\n228:     virtual void stopEnvironment(const Prompt& prompt) = 0;\n229:     virtual void markUsed(const Prompt& prompt) = 0;\n230:     virtual void setCurrentPrompt(const Prompt& prompt) = 0;\n231:     virtual std::string getCurrentNetwork() const = 0;\n232:     virtual void clearCurrentPrompt() = 0;\n233: };\n234: \n235: class DockerToolRunner : public ToolRunner {\n236: public:\n237:     virtual ~DockerToolRunner() = default;\n238:     // Constructor (in implementation) will take ContainerManager* and ComposeManager*.\n239: };\n240: ```\n241: \n242: ---\n243: \n244: ## 3. System Architecture\n245: \n246: The architecture includes both host and Docker execution paths, with mandatory dependency check and container pooling. The `SystemToolRegistry` has been eliminated — all tool dispatch (both C++ system handlers and command-based subprocess tools) goes through `SkillManager`'s handler registry.\n247: \n248: ```mermaid\n249: graph TB\n250:     User((User))\n251:     DeepSeek[(\"DeepSeek API\")]\n252: \n253:     subgraph \"Agent Process\"\n254:         Core[AgentCore]\n255:         Context[ContextManager]\n256:         SkillMgr[SkillManager]\n257:         SkillMgr_Handlers[m_handlers: xBash, xRead, xGitCommand, ...]\n258:         HostRunner[HostToolRunner]\n259:         DockerRunner[DockerToolRunner]\n260:         SkillRunner[SkillRunner]\n261:         InfEngine[SchemaInferenceEngine]\n262:         DepResolver[DependencyResolver]\n263:         Persistence[PersistenceStore]\n264:         ContainerMgr[ContainerManager]\n265:         ComposeMgr[ComposeManager]\n266:     end\n267: \n268:     subgraph \"Persistence\"\n269:         DB[(.a0/db/sessions.db)]\n270:     end\n271: \n272:     subgraph \"Docker Engine\"\n273:         Containers[(Containers)]\n274:         ComposeStacks[(Compose Stacks)]\n275:     end\n276: \n277:     subgraph \"Filesystem\"\n278:         SkillsDir[(skills/)]\n279:     end\n280: \n281:     User --> Core\n282:     Core --> SkillMgr\n283:     Core --> DepResolver\n284:     Core --> HostRunner\n285:     Core --> DockerRunner\n286:     Core --> SkillRunner\n287:     Core --> InfEngine\n288:     SkillMgr --> SkillMgr_Handlers\n289:     SkillMgr --> HostRunner\n290:     SkillMgr --> DockerRunner\n291:     SkillRunner --> DepResolver\n292:     SkillRunner --> DeepSeek\n293:     SkillRunner --> SkillMgr\n294:     SkillRunner --> HostRunner\n295:     SkillRunner --> DockerRunner\n296:     InfEngine --> DeepSeek\n297:     InfEngine --> SkillMgr\n298:     Core --> Persistence\n299:     Persistence --> DB\n300:     SkillMgr --> SkillsDir\n301: \n302:     DockerRunner --> ContainerMgr\n303:     DockerRunner --> ComposeMgr\n304:     ContainerMgr --> Containers\n305:     ComposeMgr --> ComposeStacks\n306: ```\n307: \n308: **Caption**: `SkillManager` owns both the manifest index (loaded from `skills/`) and the `m_handlers` registry of C++ system tool handlers. It dispatches to `HostToolRunner`/`DockerToolRunner` for command-based tools. All built-in tools (bash, read, edit, git, docker, etc.) are registered as handlers on `SkillManager` at startup.\n309: \n310: ---\n311: \n312: ## 4. Detailed Data Flow\n313: \n314: The following sequence diagrams show the execution paths for skills and Docker‑based tools.\n315: \n316: ### 4.1 Skill Execution with Dependency Check and Eager Tool Calls\n317: \n318: ```mermaid\n319: sequenceDiagram\n320:     participant User\n321:     participant Core\n322:     participant SkillRunner\n323:     participant DepResolver\n324:     participant ToolRunner\n325:     participant list_files\n326:     participant DeepSeek\n327:     participant extract_json\n328: \n329:     User->>Core: \"find files in /home related to proposals\"\n330:     Core->>SkillRunner: run(skill, {goal:\"find files in /home related to proposals\"})\n331:     SkillRunner->>DepResolver: checkSkillDependencies(skill)\n332:     alt missing dependencies\n333:         DepResolver-->>SkillRunner: [\"missing_tool\"]\n334:         SkillRunner-->>Core: error(\"missing dependencies: missing_tool\")\n335:         Core-->>User: error\n336:     else dependencies satisfied\n337:         DepResolver-->>SkillRunner: ok\n338:         SkillRunner->>SkillRunner: expandPrompt: replace {{goal}} with user goal\n339:         SkillRunner->>SkillRunner: parse {{tool:list_files path=\"/home\"}}\n340:         SkillRunner->>ToolRunner: run(list_files, {path:\"/home\"})\n341:         ToolRunner-->>SkillRunner: [\"f1\",\"f2\",\"f3\"]\n342:         SkillRunner->>SkillRunner: substitute tool result into prompt\n343:         SkillRunner->>DeepSeek: complete(expanded prompt)\n344:         DeepSeek-->>SkillRunner: \"[\\\"f1\\\",\\\"f3\\\"]\"\n345:         loop each validator (extract_json)\n346:             SkillRunner->>ToolRunner: run(validator, currentValue)\n347:             alt validator returns error\n348:                 ToolRunner-->>SkillRunner: \"ERROR: invalid \n... (output truncated at 8192 bytes)","role":"tool","tool_call_id":"call_00_tczmVLDMwyXUPPyHXArJ4550"},{"content":"","role":"assistant","tool_calls":[{"function":{"arguments":"{\"file_path\":\"/home/pc/projects/opensassi/a0/.a0/worktrees/a0-session-7aaf7148/technical-specification.md\",\"offset\":348}","name":"read"},"id":"call_00_s69ZUYENHmtXL0AY4HZF1667","type":"function"}]},{"content":"348:                 ToolRunner-->>SkillRunner: \"ERROR: invalid JSON\"\n349:                 SkillRunner->>SkillRunner: prefix \"VALIDATOR_ERROR:\"\n350:             else\n351:                 ToolRunner-->>SkillRunner: transformedValue\n352:             end\n353:         end\n354:         SkillRunner-->>Core: [\"f1\"]\n355:         Core-->>User: result\n356:     end\n357: ```\n358: \n359: ### 4.2 Docker Tool Execution (Containerized)\n360: \n361: ```mermaid\n362: sequenceDiagram\n363:     participant SkillRunner\n364:     participant DockerRunner\n365:     participant ContainerMgr\n366:     participant Docker\n367: \n368:     SkillRunner->>DockerRunner: run(tool, params)\n369:     DockerRunner->>ContainerMgr: acquireContainer(tool)\n370:     ContainerMgr->>ContainerMgr: lookup/start container (shared or per‑tool)\n371:     ContainerMgr-->>DockerRunner: containerId\n372:     DockerRunner->>DockerRunner: build command (args mode or stdin)\n373:     DockerRunner->>Docker: docker exec -i <containerId> sh -c '<command>'\n374:     Docker-->>DockerRunner: stdout/stderr\n375:     DockerRunner-->>SkillRunner: result\n376: ```\n377: \n378: **Note**: When a skill declares a `composeFile`, the `SkillRunner` first calls `ComposeManager::startEnvironment` to bring up the compose stack; the tool container is then attached to the resulting network.\n379: \n380: ---\n381: \n382: ## 5. Testing Requirements\n383: \n384: ### 5.1 Unit Tests (Google Test)\n385: \n386: | Class                | Test Case                                                   | Verification                                       |\n387: | -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |\n388: | `ToolRunner`         | `run` with `split_lines` tool                               | Input \"a\\nb\\nc\" → output `[\"a\",\"b\",\"c\"]`           |\n389: | `ToolRunner`         | `run` with `bash` tool                                      | Input \"echo hello\" → output \"hello\\n\"              |\n390: | `ToolRunner`         | `run` with `args` mode and object params                    | Command receives `--file=test.txt` style arguments |\n391: | `ToolRunner`         | `run` with a command that sleeps 31 seconds                 | Returns `\"ERROR: timeout\"` (enforces timeoutSecs)  |\n392: | `ToolRunner`         | `runStreaming` basic echo                                   | onChunk called with output, handle.isDone() true   |\n393: | `SkillRunner`        | `expandPrompt` with `{{goal}}` placeholder                  | Substitutes value from `params[\"goal\"]`            |\n394: | `SkillRunner`        | `expandPrompt` with eager tool call                         | Eager execution, substitution                      |\n395: | `SkillRunner`        | `expandPrompt` with `{{tool_call:...}}`                     | Short name substitution                            |\n396: | `SkillRunner`        | `runValidators` with failing validator                      | Result starts with `\"VALIDATOR_ERROR: ERROR: ...\"` |\n397: | `SkillRunner`        | `execute` when dependencies missing                         | Returns error message, does not call LLM           |\n398: | `SkillRegistry`      | `loadFromDirectory` with malformed JSON                     | Skips file, logs warning, continues                |\n399: | `DependencyResolver` | `checkPromptDependencies` on prompt with missing tool       | Returns false, missing list includes the tool      |\n400: | `AgentCore`          | `processGoal` with exact prompt name match                  | Uses the prompt, does not infer a new one          |\n401: | `AgentCore`          | `processGoal` with non‑existent goal                        | Falls back to forked tool-calling loop             |\n402: | `AgentCore`          | `processGoal` forked loop max turns exceeded                | Returns `\"ERROR: max tool call turns exceeded\"`    |\n403: \n404: ### 5.2 End‑to‑End Tests (against mock DeepSeek)\n405: \n406: #### Positive Tests\n407: \n408: | ID     | Scenario        | Steps                                                                                                                    | Expected                                                   |\n409: | ------ | --------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------- |\n410: | E2E‑01 | First run       | Start agent with empty components dir                                                                                    | Built‑in tools and meta‑skills created under `components/` |\n411: | E2E‑02 | Infer new tool  | Send goal: \"create a tool that counts lines in a file\"                                                                   | New tool `count_lines` appears; can be invoked             |\n412: | E2E‑03 | Use tool        | Invoke `count_lines` with `{path:\"/etc/passwd\"}`                                                                         | Returns number of lines                                    |\n413: | E2E‑04 | Infer new prompt/skill | Send goal: \"create a skill that lists files in a directory and filters those containing 'log' using list_files and grep\" | New prompt appears; dependencies correct |\n414: | E2E‑05 | Use prompt       | Invoke prompt with `{directory:\"/var/log\"}`                                                                               | Returns array of existing files with \"log\" in name         |\n415: \n416: #### Negative E2E Tests (Critical for Guardrails)\n417: \n418: | ID     | Scenario                      | Steps                                                                               | Expected                                                       |\n419: | ------ | ----------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |\n420: | E2E‑N1 | Skill with missing dependency | Create skill that depends on `nonexistent_tool`, then invoke it                     | Error message: `missing dependencies: nonexistent_tool`        |\n421: | E2E‑N2 | Tool that hangs               | Invoke tool that runs `sleep 100`                                                   | Returns `\"ERROR: timeout\"` within 32 seconds                   |\n422: | E2E‑N3 | Skill using `{{goal}}`        | Create skill with prompt `\"Process: {{goal}}\"`, invoke with goal \"test\"             | LLM receives `\"Process: test\"`                                 |\n423: | E2E‑N4 | Tool with `args` mode         | Create tool with `inputMode: \"args\"`, command `wc -l`, params `{\"input\":\"a\\nb\\nc\"}` | Command receives arguments correctly (exact behaviour defined) |\n424: \n425: ### 5.3 Docker‑Specific Tests\n426: \n427: #### Unit Tests (with mock Docker CLI)\n428: \n429: | Class                 | Test Case                          | Verification                                         |\n430: | --------------------- | ---------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |\n431: | `ContainerManager`    | `acquireContainer` with HIGH trust | Same container ID for two different high‑trust tools |\n432: | `ContainerManager`    | `acquireContainer` with LOW trust  | Different containers for different tool names        |\n433: | `ContainerManager`    | `pruneIdleContainers`              | Container idle > timeout removed                     |\n434: | `DependencyInstaller` | `installDependencies`              | Idempotent installation                              |\n435: | `ComposeManager`      | `startEnvironment`                 | `docker-compose up -d` called only once per skill    |\n436: | `DockerToolRunner`    | `run` with `args` mode             | Command arguments passed correctly inside container  |\n437: | `DockerToolRunner`    | `run` with timeout                 | Timeout enforced (kills container command)           |\n438: | `DockerToolRunner`    | `runStreaming` pooled              | StreamHandle returned, chunks via callback           |\n439: | `DockerToolRunner`    | `runStreaming` ephemeral        \n... (output truncated at 8192 bytes)","role":"tool","tool_call_id":"call_00_s69ZUYENHmtXL0AY4HZF1667"},{"content":"","role":"assistant","tool_calls":[{"function":{"arguments":"{\"file_path\":\"/home/pc/projects/opensassi/a0/.a0/worktrees/a0-session-7aaf7148/technical-specification.md\",\"offset\":439}","name":"read"},"id":"call_00_2wil39BAxXtgdy22NTYQ3987","type":"function"}]},{"content":"439: | `DockerToolRunner`    | `runStreaming` ephemeral           | StreamHandle returned, `docker run --rm` used        |\n440: \n441: #### End‑to‑End Tests (with real Docker daemon)\n442: \n443: | ID     | Scenario                                     | Expected                             |\n444: | ------ | -------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------ |\n445: | E2E‑D1 | Basic tool in default image (`ubuntu:22.04`) | Output matches command               |\n446: | E2E‑D2 | `aptDependencies` installed correctly        | Tool can use installed package       |\n447: | E2E‑D3 | Trust level HIGH – container sharing         | Two tools run in same container      |\n448: | E2E‑D4 | Trust level LOW – isolation                  | Each tool gets its own container     |\n449: | E2E‑D5 | Skill with `docker-compose.yml`              | Services start, tool can connect     |\n450: | E2E‑D6 | Container pruning                            | Idle container removed after timeout |\n451: \n452: ---\n453: \n454: ## 6. CLI Entry Point\n455: \n456: ```bash\n457: agent --components-dir <path> [--env-file <path>] [--a0-dir <path>] [--resume <session-id>]\n458:       [--api-key <key>] [--mock-api <url>]\n459:       [--docker-host <url>] [--container-idle-timeout <seconds>]\n460:       [--max-idle-containers <count>] [--default-docker-image <image>] [--no-docker]\n461: ```\n462: \n463: - `--a0-dir` : Root directory for non-committed agent artifacts (default `./.a0`). Created on startup if missing; on first creation, automatically appended to `.gitignore` when CWD is a git repository. All runtime state (b1 socket/pid, SQLite database, skills store, logs) is scoped under this directory.\n464: - `--components-dir` : Root directory for components (default `./components`).\n465: - `--env-file` : Path to `.env` file to load (default `./.env`). Each line is `KEY=VALUE`; `#` comments and blank lines are skipped. **The implementation must overwrite existing environment variables** (i.e., use `setenv(key, val, 1)`).\n466: \n467: - `--api-key` : DeepSeek API key; if not provided, read from environment (see precedence below).\n468: - `--mock-api` : Override the API URL (for testing, e.g., `http://localhost:8080`).\n469: \n470: **Docker‑specific flags**:\n471: \n472: - `--docker-host` : Docker daemon socket URL (default `unix:///var/run/docker.sock`).\n473: - `--container-idle-timeout` : Seconds after which an idle container is pruned (default `300`).\n474: - `--max-idle-containers` : Maximum number of idle containers allowed per pool (default `10`).\n475: - `--default-docker-image` : Default image when tool does not specify `dockerImage` (default `ubuntu:22.04`).\n476: - `--no-docker` : Disable Docker integration; fall back to host runner for all tools.\n477: \n478: **Environment variables** (override defaults):\n479: \n480: - `A0_DIR` — default `.a0/` root (overridden by `--a0-dir`)\n481: - `A0_DOCKER_HOST`\n482: - `A0_CONTAINER_IDLE_TIMEOUT`\n483: - `A0_MAX_IDLE_CONTAINERS`\n484: - `A0_DEFAULT_DOCKER_IMAGE`\n485: \n486: **API key precedence (highest to lowest)**:\n487: \n488: 1. `--api-key` command line argument.\n489: 2. `DEEPSEEK_API_KEY` environment variable (from parent process).\n490: 3. `DEEPSEEK_API_KEY` set in `--env-file` (default `.env`).\n491: 4. `DEEPSEEK_API_KEY` set in `~/.deepseek.env`.\n492: \n493: **Example**:\n494: \n495: ```bash\n496: export DEEPSEEK_API_KEY=\"sk-...\"\n497: agent --components-dir ./my_components --container-idle-timeout 600 --max-idle-containers 5\n498: ```\n499: \n500: ---\n501: \n502: ## 7. Development Instructions (Revised)\n503: \n504: ### 7.1 Build Setup\n505: \n506: **Requirements**:\n507: \n508: - C++17 compiler (GCC 9+, Clang 12+, or MSVC 2019+)\n509: - CMake 3.15+\n510: - libcurl (for HTTP requests to DeepSeek API)\n511: - jsoncpp or nlohmann/json (JSON parsing)\n512: - (Optional) gcov/lcov for coverage, Google Test for unit tests\n513: - **Docker** (for containerized execution) – optional but required for Docker features\n514: \n515: **CMakeLists.txt** (as in original, plus `ENABLE_TRACE` and `ENABLE_COVERAGE` options). The Docker sub‑module sources reside in `./src/docker/` and are compiled into the main library.\n516: \n517: ### 7.2 Startup Sequence\n518: \n519: On launch, `main.cpp` follows this order:\n520: \n521: 1. **Parse flags (two-pass)** — extract `--env-file` first, then all flags including `--a0-dir`.\n522: 2. **Resolve API key** — `--api-key` → `DEEPSEEK_API_KEY` env → `.env` → `~/.deepseek.env`.\n523: 3. **Initialize `.a0/`** — `ensureA0Dir(a0Dir)` creates the directory if missing. On first creation, if the CWD is a git repository, appends `.a0/` to `.gitignore`.\n524: 4. **`--kill-all` cleanup** — reads `.a0/b1.pid` and the c2 PID file, sends SIGTERM/SIGKILL, unlinks sockets, exits.\n525: 5. **Component construction** — skill registry, tool runners, Docker managers, etc.\n526: 6. **b1 auto-launch** — if not `--no-b1` and not in `--run` mode, start/connect to b1 supervisor using paths under `a0Dir`.\n527: 7. **`--run` mode** — execute a skill non-interactively and exit.\n528: 8. **Interactive REPL** — `core.run()` blocks until EOF.\n529: \n530: ### 7.3 Implementation Plan (Test‑Driven, 90% Coverage)\n531: \n532: Follow these steps **in order**:\n533: \n534: #### Step 1: Write individual specification files for each source module\n535: \n536: - For each `.cpp` file, create a `.spec.md` describing input/output contracts, error handling, and edge cases.\n537: \n538: #### Step 1b: Interface assertion tests\n539: \n540: - Before writing any implementation, create compile‑time or runtime assertions that verify each interface’s contract is internally consistent.\n541:   - For `ToolRunner`: write a test that expects `run` to handle `inputMode == \"args\"` and enforce a timeout (even with a stub).\n542:   - For `SkillRunner`: write a test that passes a `params` object with a `{{goal}}` placeholder and asserts that the expanded prompt contains the substituted value.\n543:   - For `SkillManager`: write a test that registers a handler via `registerHandler`, calls `executeTool` with the exact key, and asserts the handler output is returned. Also test wildcard resolution (`system:git:*` with `_subcommand`).\n544:   - These tests initially fail against stubs, forcing the implementer to provide the required behaviour.\n545: \n546: #### Step 2: Write stub implementations with no logic\n547: \n548: - Implement all functions with empty bodies or `return {};` (or throw `std::logic_error(\"stub\")`).\n549: - Ensure the code compiles and links.\n550: \n551: #### Step 3: Implement tests against the stub\n552: \n553: - Use Google Test.\n554: - Write unit tests that **expect failure** (assertions that the stub does not yet satisfy the spec).\n555: - Also write “stub tests” that verify the stub returns default values without crashing.\n556: - All tests should pass against the stub **only** for trivial cases; most functional tests fail.\n557: \n558: #### Step 4: Implement code incrementally\n559: \n560: - For each function, write the minimal implementation to pass its tests.\n561: - Commit after each passing test.\n562: - Use **TDD red‑green‑refactor** cycle.\n563: \n564: #### Step 5: Ensure tests pass – when unsure, consult spec file\n565: \n566: - The spec file is **authoritative**; fix either the test or the implementation accordingly.\n567: \n568: #### Step 6: Use code coverage tool – enforce 90% coverage\n569: \n570: - Configure CMake with `--coverage` (GCC/Clang).\n571: - Run `lcov --capture --directory . --output-file coverage.info`\n572: - Generate HTML report: `genhtml coverage.info --output-directory coverage_html`\n573: - **Requirement**: line coverage ≥90%, function coverage ≥90%, branch coverage ≥90%.\n574: - Any uncovered lines must be justified (e.g., defensive `assert` or unreachable error handling).\n575: \n576: #### Step 7: Session persistence with SQLite\n577: \n578: - Wire `PersistenceStore` (SqliteStore) through AgentCore at startup.\n579: - Record every user message, LLM invocation, tool call, and result to the `message` table.\n580: - Use sub-session tracking (subSessionId + seq) for the forked tool-calling loop.\n581: - Enable `ValidationEngine` to re\n... (output truncated at 8192 bytes)","role":"tool","tool_call_id":"call_00_2wil39BAxXtgdy22NTYQ3987"},{"content":"","role":"assistant","tool_calls":[{"function":{"arguments":"{\"file_path\":\"/home/pc/projects/opensassi/a0/.a0/worktrees/a0-session-7aaf7148/technical-specification.md\",\"offset\":581}","name":"read"},"id":"call_00_QNiGqB1WnlAPMLSOVq782965","type":"function"}]},{"content":"581: - Enable `ValidationEngine` to read historical invocations from the `invocation` table for upgrade validation.\n582: - Implement streaming persistence: `Stream` + `StreamChunk` tables for live tool output recording.\n583: \n584: #### Step 8: Set up end‑to‑end testing with mock DeepSeek API\n585: \n586: - Create a mock HTTP server (e.g., using `cpp-httplib` or a simple Python script) that returns fixture data.\n587: - Fixtures stored in `test/fixtures/deepseek/`.\n588: \n589: #### Step 8a: Negative E2E tests\n590: \n591: - In addition to happy‑path tests, write end‑to‑end tests that deliberately trigger error conditions:\n592:   - Missing dependency.\n593:   - Timeout.\n594:   - Parameter substitution.\n595:   - `args` mode.\n596: - Each negative test must verify that the agent returns an appropriate error message and does not crash.\n597: \n598: #### Step 9: Run E2E tests after every change (CI hook)\n599: \n600: - They must pass before merging.\n601: \n602: #### Step 10: Implement Docker sub‑module\n603: \n604: The Docker sub‑module is a **required** part of the agent for containerized tool execution. Its complete technical specification is located in `./src/docker/technical-specification.md` and the implementation source code resides in `./src/docker/`. The key implementation phases are:\n605: \n606: 10.1 Implement `ContainerManager` and `DependencyInstaller` using Docker CLI calls (via `popen` or libcurl over the Docker socket).\n607: 10.2 Implement `DockerToolRunner` and integrate into `AgentCore` (tool runner selection based on `dockerImage` presence).\n608: 10.3 Implement `ComposeManager` for skill‑level compose environments.\n609: 10.4 Add pruning logic and CLI flags as described in Section 6.\n610: 10.5 Write unit tests with a mock Docker executable (e.g., a bash script that simulates `docker` commands).\n611: 10.6 Run Docker‑specific E2E tests with a real Docker daemon (if available in CI).\n612: \n613: All Docker‑related code must be placed in `./src/docker/`, with its own `CMakeLists.txt` included from the top‑level `CMakeLists.txt`.\n614: \n615: #### Step 11: Implement Skills sub‑module\n616: \n617: The Skills sub‑module is a **required** part of the agent for tool/skill lifecycle management, distribution, and version validation. Its complete technical specification is located in `./src/skills/technical-specification.md` and the implementation source code resides in `./src/skills/`. The key implementation phases are:\n618: \n619: 11.1 Implement `SkillLoader` — directory walking, `skill.json` parsing, three-tier namespace index.\n620: 11.2 Implement `SkillManager` facade — qualified name resolution, `addTool`/`addPrompt`, CLI dispatch.\n621: 11.3 Implement `VersionManager` — `.a0/store/` archival, `lock.json` refcounting, GC.\n622: 11.4 Implement `ValidationEngine` — historical log replay, output comparison, compat bridge execution.\n623: 11.5 Wire `SkillManager` into `AgentCore`.\n624: 11.6 Add `a0 skill` CLI subcommand routing in `main.cpp`.\n625: 11.7 Write unit tests with fixture skill trees and mock historical logs.\n626: 11.8 Write integration tests for install/remove/gc with a mock GitHub endpoint.\n627: \n628: All built-in tool handlers are registered directly on `SkillManager` via `registerHandler()` in `main.cpp`'s `xRegisterSystemHandlers()`. Each handler is a free-standing function in `namespace a0` (`xBash`, `xRead`, `xGitCommand`, etc.) returning `HandlerResult`. `SkillManager::executeTool()` resolves through exact match → 2-part alias → wildcard → command tool subprocess, providing a single dispatch path for all tools.\n629: \n630: All skills‑related code must be placed in `./src/skills/`, with its own `CMakeLists.txt` included from the top‑level `CMakeLists.txt`.\n631: \n632: #### Step 12: Implement CommandRunner utility\n633: \n634: The `CommandRunner` is a stateless utility class that wraps all subprocess creation in the agent. Every `fork()`, `exec()`, `pipe()`, `alarm()` call is isolated here — no other class manages processes directly.\n635: \n636: 12.1 Implement `CommandRunner::run()` — single command execution with stdin piping, alarm timeout, stdout/stderr capture, and process group management.\n637: 12.2 Implement `CommandRunner::runAll()` — parallel command execution via N-child fork + waitpid loop, configurable `maxParallel`.\n638: 12.3 Implement `CommandRunner::shellEscape()` — single-quote shell escaping for safe argument passing.\n639: 12.4 Refactor `SubprocessToolRunner` to delegate all subprocess calls to `CommandRunner::run()`, retaining only command-building logic (args mode, stdin mode).\n640: 12.5 Refactor `DockerCLIWrapper` to use `CommandRunner::run()` instead of its own `execSimple`/`execWithTimeout`/`shellEscape` internals.\n641: 12.6 Refactor `DockerToolRunnerImpl::execDockerRun` to delegate to `CommandRunner::run()`.\n642: 12.7 Refactor `ValidationEngine` to use `CommandRunner::run()` for replay and compat bridge execution.\n643: 12.8 Remove duplicate `shellEscape`, `handleAlarm`, signal handler, and fork/exec/pipe code from all other files.\n644: 12.9 Write unit tests for CommandRunner (echo, timeout, pipe, parallel, edge cases).\n645: \n646: ---\n647: \n648: ## 8. File Layout\n649: \n650: ```\n651: project/\n652: ├── CMakeLists.txt\n653: ├── src/\n654: │   ├── a0_dir.h/.cpp                    # .a0/ directory lifecycle (create, gitignore)\n655: │   ├── command_runner.h/.cpp            # All subprocess management (fork/exec/pipe/alarm)\n656: │   ├── handler_results.h                # HandlerResult struct for system tool dispatch\n657: │   ├── system_handlers.h/.cpp           # Free-standing C++ handler functions (xBash, xRead, xGitCommand, etc.)\n658: │   ├── main.cpp\n659: │   ├── agent_core.cpp/.h\n660: │   ├── tool_runner.cpp/.h               # HostToolRunner + DockerToolRunner\n661: │   ├── skill_runner.cpp/.h\n662: │   ├── deepseek_provider.cpp/.h\n663: │   ├── context_manager.cpp/.h\n664: │   ├── schema_inference_engine.cpp/.h\n665: │   ├── dependency_resolver.cpp/.h\n666: │   ├── trace.h\n667: │   ├── stream_registry.h/.cpp           # Streaming IPC support\n668: │   ├── docker_security_filter.h/.cpp    # Docker command filtering\n669: │   ├── docker/                          # Docker sub‑module (required)\n670: │   │   ├── technical-specification.md\n671: │   │   ├── container_manager.cpp/.h\n672: │   │   ├── compose_manager.cpp/.h\n673: │   │   ├── docker_tool_runner.cpp/.h\n674: │   │   ├── dependency_installer.cpp/.h\n675: │   │   └── CMakeLists.txt\n676: │   └── skills/                          # Skills sub‑module (required)\n677: │       ├── technical-specification.md   # Full skills integration spec\n678: │       ├── skills.h                     # Data structures + SkillManager facade + ToolHandler typedef\n679: │       ├── skill_manager.cpp\n680: │       ├── skill_loader.h/.cpp\n681: │       ├── version_manager.h/.cpp\n682: │       ├── validation_engine.h/.cpp\n683: │       └── CMakeLists.txt\n684: ├── test/\n685: │   ├── unit/\n686: │   │   ├── test_tool_runner.cpp\n687: │   │   ├── test_skill_runner.cpp\n688: │   │   ├── test_docker_*.cpp            # Docker unit tests\n689: │   │   ├── test_skill_manager.cpp\n690: │   │   ├── test_skill_loader.cpp\n691: │   │   ├── test_version_manager.cpp\n692: │   │   └── test_validation_engine.cpp\n693: │   ├── e2e/\n694: │   │   ├── mock_deepseek_server.py\n695: │   │   ├── fixtures/\n696: │   │   └── run_e2e_tests.sh\n697: ├── skills/                          # created at runtime — three-tier namespace\n698: │   ├── system/                      # shipped with agent (read-only)\n699: │   ├── local/                       # agent-created (writable)\n700: │   └── github_<user>/               # installed from GitHub (read-only)\n701: ├── .a0/                             # ag\n... (output truncated at 8192 bytes)","role":"tool","tool_call_id":"call_00_QNiGqB1WnlAPMLSOVq782965"},{"content":"","role":"assistant","tool_calls":[{"function":{"arguments":"{\"file_path\":\"/home/pc/projects/opensassi/a0/.a0/worktrees/a0-session-7aaf7148/technical-specification.md\",\"offset\":701}","name":"read"},"id":"call_00_AFxLnAEN1VuH6ft2hydb0105","type":"function"}]},{"content":"701: ├── .a0/                             # agent internal state (auto-created, gitignored)\n702: │   ├── b1.pid                       # b1 supervisor PID file\n703: │   ├── b1.sock                      # b1 supervisor Unix socket\n704: │   ├── db/\n705: │   │   └── sessions.db              # SQLite session database\n706: │   ├── store/                       # version archive keyed by commit hash\n707: \n708: │   └── lock.json                    # version refcounts + metadata\n709: \n710: └── coverage_html/                   # generated after coverage run\n711: ```\n712: \n713: ---\n714: \n715: ## 9. Development Workflow Summary\n716: \n717: 1. Write spec files for each module.\n718: 2. **Write interface assertion tests** that codify the contract.\n719: 3. Write stub implementations.\n720: 4. Write unit tests (both stub‑passing and failing functional tests).\n721: 5. Implement code iteratively until all tests pass.\n722: 6. Run coverage tool; ensure ≥90% coverage.\n723: 7. Run **positive and negative** E2E tests with mock DeepSeek API; fix any failures.\n724: 8. Implement Docker sub‑module (following `./src/docker/technical-specification.md`).\n725: 9. Run Docker‑specific tests (unit and E2E with real Docker).\n726: 10. Implement Skills sub‑module (following `./src/skills/technical-specification.md`).\n727: 11. Implement `CommandRunner` utility — centralize all fork/exec/pipe/alarm code.\n728: 12. Enable `-DTRACE` for debug builds; keep trace logs for diagnosis.\n729: 13. Commit and CI verifies all tests + coverage.\n730: \n731: ---\n732: \n733: ## 10. Future Extensions\n734: \n735: - Streaming LLM responses and validator chains.\n736: - C++ compilation of performance‑critical validators.\n737: - Input/output transformation mappers in validator objects (e.g., JSONPath).\n738: - Sandboxing for `bash` tool (command allowlist).\n739: - Native `mustache` templating for prompt expansion.\n740: - **LXC backend** as alternative to Docker (for environments without Docker).\n741: - Resource limits (CPU/memory) per tool in Docker.\n742: \n743: ---\n744: \n745: ## Appendix A: Docker Integration Sub‑Module Specification\n746: \n747: The complete technical specification for the Docker sub‑module is provided in a separate document: `./src/docker/technical-specification.md`. It includes detailed class specifications, sequence diagrams, configuration options, and testing requirements. The sub‑module is **required** for containerized execution; when `--no-docker` is used, the agent reverts to host‑only execution, but the Docker code is still compiled.\n748: \n749: **Location**: `./src/docker/technical-specification.md`  \n750: **Source code**: `./src/docker/`\n751: \n752: ## Appendix B: Skills Sub‑Module Specification\n753: \n754: The complete technical specification for the Skills sub‑module is provided in a separate document: `./src/skills/technical-specification.md`. It includes detailed class specifications, sequence diagrams, configuration options, and testing requirements. The sub‑module is **required** — it implements a three-tier namespace system with version validation via historical log replay and GitHub distribution support.\n755: \n756: `SkillManager` serves as the unified tool dispatch layer, replacing `SystemToolRegistry`. A handler registry (`m_handlers`) holds C++ functions registered at startup by `xRegisterSystemHandlers()` in `main.cpp`. `executeTool()` and `schemas()` provide the single point of dispatch and schema generation for the LLM.\n757: \n758: **Location**: `./src/skills/technical-specification.md`  \n759: **Source code**: `./src/skills/`\n760: \n761: ---","role":"tool","tool_call_id":"call_00_AFxLnAEN1VuH6ft2hydb0105"}],"model":"deepseek-chat","tools":[{"function":{"description":"Browse the skill tree by path. Lists available skills with descriptions.","name":"show_skills","parameters":{"properties":{"path":{"default":"/","description":"Skill tree path (e.g. /system/git)","type":"string"}},"required":[],"type":"object"}},"type":"function"},{"function":{"description":"Browse available tools by category. Lists tool names, descriptions, and parameters.","name":"show_skill_tools","parameters":{"properties":{"path":{"default":"/","description":"Tool tree path (e.g. /git/porcelain)","type":"string"}},"required":[],"type":"object"}},"type":"function"},{"function":{"description":"Analyze user intent and recommend skills/tools for a given prompt.","name":"tools_for_prompt","parameters":{"properties":{"prompt":{"description":"The user's prompt to analyze","type":"string"}},"required":["prompt"],"type":"object"}},"type":"function"},{"function":{"description":"Executes a given bash command in a persistent shell session with optional timeout, ensuring proper handling and security measures.\n\nBe aware: OS: linux, Shell: bash\n\nIMPORTANT: This tool is for terminal operations like git, npm, docker, etc. DO NOT use it for file operations (reading, writing, editing, searching, finding files) - use the specialized tools for this instead.\n\nBefore executing the command, please follow these steps:\n\n1. Directory Verification:\n   - If the command will create new directories or files, first use `ls` to verify the parent directory exists and is the correct location\n\n2. Command Execution:\n   - Always quote file paths that contain spaces with double quotes\n   - After ensuring proper quoting,